<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="sa0511x"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="sa" href="#sa0511x">SA (VI.A) </a>: <a href="../../FF/fnbs/ssaall.htm#sa0511x"> 511(x)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> a true noun does not exist in nature (Fenollosa): <small>Green</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="sa0511x"><li>FW 523.10-11 </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/lexrA.htm#sa0511x">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/rA/l39rA.htm#sa0511x">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#sa0511x">MS BL 47484a-049</ms> </li><li>JJA 58:189 <a name="rAd4" href="../../FF/fdra/rda.htm#rAd4">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/rA/rAd4.htm#sa0511x">Draft: III&sect;3A.4</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources"><mark>A true noun, an isolated thing, does not exist in nature.</mark> Things are only the terminal points, or rather the meeting points of actions, cross-sections cut through actions, snap-shots. Neither can a pure verb, an abstract motion, be possible in nature. The eye sees noun and verb as things in motion, motion in things, and so the Chinese conception tends to represent them. <p>But examination shows that a large number of the primitive Chinese characters, even the so-called radicals, are shorthand pictures of actions or processes.</p> <small> Ernest Fenollosa, &ldquo;The Chinese Written Character as a Medium for Poetry&rdquo;, in <a name="EFCW1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#EFCW1"><cite title="source">Instigations of Ezra Pound</cite></a> (1920) 364</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: See also <a name="n58060b" href="n58all.htm#n58060b">N58 (VI.B.30):060(b)</a>. </mm> </dd></dl>
